stance. You can test if the instance was able to connect with your camera or not (if it wasn\u2019t, check your settings to make sure apps can access it).", "Finally, it\u2019s time to take the picture. If you want to control when the picture is taken, the first line assigns an arbitrary variable and input. The program cannot proceed unless something is entered (e.g. pressing \u2018enter\u2019), and the next line takes the picture. You may see your webcam light appear shortly while the image is being taken. The third line closes the connection, and the fourth destroys all instances of accessing your camera.", "The data from your image is stored in frame. It can be converted into an array with the below code:", "When calling cv2_im.shape, the output is (480, 640, 3). Hence, the image (for my camera) is 480 by 640 pixels (the 3 represents the \u2018depth\u2019 \u2014 three values in each pixel explain how much of red, green, and blue to include to create the final pixel color).", "Now that your image has been converted into an array, matplotlib\u2019s imshow() can display it.", "A Convolutional Neural Network only takes in images of a fixed size \u2014 for example, (100, 100, 3). There\u2019s a few methods to accomplish this.", "To preserve the ratio lengths of the image, it may be helpful to crop the image.", "Where \u2018upper\u2019 and \u2018lower\u2019 is determined by location on the image (\u2018upper\u2019 for y is higher up the image, \u2018upper\u2019 for x is farther right).", "This crops the photo into a square shape.", "However, the dimensions are still 300 by 300. To fix, this, we will use Pillow once again:", "NumPy automatically converts Pillow images into arrays.", "Now that we have the NumPy array, it is simply a matter of passing it through the model.", "Based on this, with some manual coding to label the real-world label of an image, they can be labelled in a title:", "In this tutorial, you learned how to implement a simple picture-taking interface 